ar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args. Let's check the response.\n\nSo, the first thing I should do is run the mcp tool with tool \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args \"{}\". Then, based on the response, proceed accordingly.\n\nIf the response is state: waiting, I need to take the after_version from the response and call again with {\"after_version\": <number>}. If it's state: ready, then read the prompt, turn, limits, etc., and the opportunity id. Once I have that, review the case and evidence, then submit the vote.\n\nLet me structure this step by step.\n\nFirst, I need to make the initial mcp call for aar_wait_for_opportunity. Let's do that.\n\nCheck if there's a specific way to format the mcp call. The instructions say that the arguments must be a JSON string. So, when using mcp, the arguments would be {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}.\n\nWait, no. Wait. The mcp function parameters have tool and args as separate fields. Wait, looking at the tool definition for mcp:\n\nIn the tools section, the mcp function's parameters include \"tool\" and \"args\" (as a JSON string), or other actions like connect, search, etc. But for tool calls (i.e., when using mcp to call a specific tool), the usage is:\n\nmcp({ tool: \"name\", args: '{\"key\": \"value\"}' })\n\nSo, for example, when calling aar_wait_for_opportunity, the mcp call should have tool set to \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", and args as a JSON string with the necessary parameters. In the first call, the args is \"{}\", so as a string.\n\nSo the correct way is:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"mcp\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n    \"args\": \"{}\"\n  }\n}\n\nYes, because the mcp tool's parameters have \"tool\" and \"args\", and for this case, tool is \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", and args is the string \"{}\".\n\nSo first, I need to make that call.\n\nAfter that, depending on the response, proceed.\n\nLet me check the user's instructions again. The user says: \"First call mcp with {\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}.\" So exactly that.\n\nSo the next step is to call mcp with tool= \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args=\"{}\".\n\nSo I should do that first.\n\nNow, the user is instructing me to follow this process. So I'll make that tool call.\n\nLet me generate the correct JSON for the mcp tool.\n\nYes, the tool call will be:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"mcp\",\n  \"arguments\": {\n    \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n    \"args\": \"{}\"\n  }\n}\n\nYes. So that's the first step.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0373f3b154814e50b70f55","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"{\"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782776804149,"responseId":"gen-1782776804-seR2NHc7jkxnrmzI87wp","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
